        "avatar_template": "/letter_avatar_proxy/v4/letter/m/ecb155/{size}.png",
        "created_at": "2020-11-11T10:45:00.000Z",
        "cooked": "<p>Had a champagne themed dinner yesterday that paired excellently with crab rice noodles:</p>\n<p>Was wondering how I got into champagnes so had a look at my tasting notes - by pure dumb luck my first four champagnes were Benoit Lahaye, Chartogne-Taillet, Bereche and Cedric Bouchard which wasn\u2019t a bad start!</p>\n<p>I love the versatility of champagnes with food and it\u2019s a shame that they are usually relegated to the role of aperitifs when they are actually the best pairing with food, no surprise that all the bottles were emptied at the end of the night here.</p>\n<p>Also we had a Grassl Liberte, Zalto white wine and universal and a GGG to compare glasses. The Grassl Liberte is seriously impressive for champagnes and showed all the wines solidly, it achieved a good middle ground between the Zalto universal which accentuated the acidity a little too much and the white wine glass that was a little too muted for me.</p>\n<p>Last interesting thing to note was that these champagnes were perhaps made in a bygone era as they all appeared rather sweet to our palates compared to the lean, low dosage style that we have gotten used to.</p>\n<ul>\n<li>\n<a href=\"https://www.cellartracker.com/note.asp?iWine=713905&amp;iNote=8749920\" rel=\"noopener nofollow ugc\"><strong>2000 Billecart-Salmon Champagne Cuv\u00e9e Nicolas-Fran\u00e7ois Billecart</strong></a> <em>- France, Champagne (11/11/2020)</em><br>\nMost typical champagne of the night, a nod to big houses achieving an incredible quality and consistency despite their large volume. A rich champagne with brioche, citrus fruits. Some people guessed it was a Comtes from the bottle shape but this wasn\u2019t as lean as the Comtes that I had last month. Some flint on the nose that would have pointed me towards Dom actually but nowhere near as reductive. Very fresh despite being the oldest bottle, drinking well now.</li>\n<li>\n<a href=\"https://www.cellartracker.com/note.asp?iWine=1029792&amp;iNote=8749924\" rel=\"noopener nofollow ugc\"><strong>2002 Piper-Heidsieck Champagne Cuv\u00e9e Rare</strong></a> <em>- France, Champagne (11/11/2020)</em><br>\nAnother big house champagne that showed good quality and consistency. 70% chard, higher dosage than the Billecart-Salmon, more exotic and tropical fruits that were slightly coarser on the palate, but still had the rich and brioche notes that typify grandes marques.</li>\n<li>\n<a href=\"https://www.cellartracker.com/note.asp?iWine=2784096&amp;iNote=8749915\" rel=\"noopener nofollow ugc\"><strong>2006 Larmandier-Bernier Champagne Grand Cru Vieille Vigne de Cramant</strong></a> <em>- France, Champagne, Champagne Grand Cru (11/11/2020)</em><br>\nOne of the pioneers in organic farming in champagne in the 90s when production of champagne was much more industrial than artisanal. Rich, powerful champagne, plenty of red-fruited character that made people think this was a Pinot heavy champagne. Despite the low dosage (2g/l), it appeared a little sweet with the fully ripe fruit and oak usage that gave some yeasty notes. Always held back from buying this producer because of supposed variation but this was a very good bottle.</li>\n<li>\n<a href=\"https://www.cellartracker.com/note.asp?iWine=1296790&amp;iNote=8749918\" rel=\"noopener nofollow ugc\"><strong>2009 J\u00e9r\u00f4me Pr\u00e9vost Champagne La Closerie Extra Brut Les Beguines</strong></a> <em>- France, Champagne (11/11/2020)</em><br>\nFirst time having Prevost and thoroughly impressed. Generous red fruits, a powerful style of champagne with an elegant mouthcoating texture, unlike other Meunier champagnes that can be a little brutish. When the bubbles dissipated this could have passed for a white Burg with a some oxidative notes.</li>\n<li>\n<a href=\"https://www.cellartracker.com/note.asp?iWine=1315618&amp;iNote=8749923\" rel=\"noopener nofollow ugc\"><strong>2010 Vilmart &amp; Cie Champagne Premier Cru Coeur de Cuv\u00e9e</strong></a> <em>- France, Champagne, Champagne Premier Cru (11/11/2020)</em><br>\nDidn\u2019t get to try this when first popped but apparently it was showing to be very creamy and fresh on opening. When I got around to it I thought it was slightly simple and sweet, would have been a good quaffer but paled slightly in comparison to the rest. Some custard and vanilla notes, very good effort despite the difficult vintage. Vilmart has an uncommon way of winemaking of extremely high dosage, oak usage, no malo but his wines are always very well-integrated. I still liked this but at this price point I would stick to the Grand Cellier.</li>\n</ul>\n<p><a href=\"https://ibb.co/y6f1MYn\" rel=\"noopener nofollow ugc\"><img src=\"https://www.wineberserkers.com/uploads/db0731/original/3X/0/d/0d880868a96c40461489c81fe1475029d57c11ed.jpeg\" alt=\"\" data-base62-sha1=\"1VHEGe3RSuHkKwgXz02soYgzbT7\" role=\"presentation\" width=\"375\" height=\"500\"></a><br>\n<a href=\"https://ibb.co/CP5szrF\" rel=\"noopener nofollow ugc\"><img src=\"https://www.wineberserkers.com/uploads/db0731/original/3X/e/5/e570e5c8bff3a1f18a5d16c2bf0408b53c7ccbd0.jpeg\" alt=\"\" data-base62-sha1=\"wJJdO6PUV3sctxMFdGjQdUDLKog\" role=\"presentation\" width=\"499\" height=\"500\"></a></p>",
